
First: Don't install this if you like PRIVACY!
These are primarily notes to myself for when I have to install this again
five years from now.

It expects to find its configuration in /etc/httpv.
You put keys in here (example.key) and certificate configs (domain.conf)
and use Let's Encrypt (or whatever you want) to generate certificate
chains (example.domain.cert).

In /etc/httpv there should also be config.txt, which configures httpv itself.

So for example we might have, in /etc/httpv:

  key31337.key    (RSA key; "BEGIN PRIVATE KEY" format like PEM)
  tom7.org.chain  (Certs; "BEGIN CERTIFICATE" format; typically two)
  config.txt

And your config.txt might look like:

  session-tickets true

  default-port 81
  user nobody

  # expensive!
  max-plaintext-size 16

  iv-strategy data

  heartbleed A message to return\x00

  # Fixed server random. Up to 32 bytes.
  server-random \x20\x20\x20hi\x20:)\x20\x20\x20

  key /etc/httpv/key31337.key
  cert /etc/httpv/tom7.org.chain

    host tom7.org
      alias www.tom7.org
      alias h4x3r.tom7.org

You can have lots of hosts and aliases, with the same key or different ones.
See config.cc to to see what options exist.

use "make install" to build the executable and put it in /usr/local/sbin/httpv.exe

You can generate a key with multi-gen.exe. You'd need to modify the
parameters in the source code.

renew.exe uses config.txt to determine what certificates need to exist,
and then checks them or fetches them from Let's Encrypt. You shouldn't
need openssl, but you need certbot and some way to answer the ACME
challenges (I'm using the acme-dns thing).

To run this as a service, create
/etc/systemd/system/httpv.service


[Unit]
Description=HTTPV
# Wait until networking is up.
# could also depend on apache2.service if you want
After=network.target

[Service]
ExecStart=/usr/local/sbin/httpv.exe
# Automatically restart the service if it crashes
Restart=always
RestartSec=5

# Maximum number of forked children (concurrent requests).
# You can make this lower, but when people "security scan" me
# and/or the scrapers are in full effect, I do see it exceed
# 256 tasks. The symptom is "fork: Resource temporarily unavailable"
# in systemd logs.
TasksMax=512

NoNewPrivileges=yes

# The daemon doesn't write files, so just lock it down.
# But the approach below is better.
# PrivateTmp=yes
# ProtectSystem=full
# ProtectHome=yes

# In fact, just construct the filesystem.
TemporaryFileSystem=/
# Dash in front of these means mount them.
BindReadOnlyPaths=-/usr/local/sbin/httpv.exe
BindReadOnlyPaths=-/etc/httpv
# Actually, also need /etc/passwd etc. to swich users
BindReadOnlyPaths=-/etc
# Need to find some shared objects. use "ldd httpv.exe" to see what paths are needed
BindReadOnlyPaths=-/lib
BindReadOnlyPaths=-/lib64
PrivateDevices=yes

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target


Then:
systemctl daemon-reload
systemctl restart httpv
systemctl status httpv


I also renew certificates automatically from cron. I just added
a "renew-certs" script in /etc/cron.daily:

#!/bin/bash

# Make sure compilers etc. are in path.
export PATH=/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin:/usr/games:/usr/local/games:/snap/bin

set -e
cd /usr/src/tom7misc/httpv
make renew.exe
./renew.exe

